    intro: "Dog food is the decision you make three times a day for the next decade. Get it roughly right and most other health questions get easier; get it wrong and you'll pay for it in itchy skin, recurring ear infections, and a vet bill for \\\"unexplained\\\" GI issues. The category is also the single most misleading aisle in pet retail — packaging wins shelf space, not ingredient quality.\\n\\nStart with the AAFCO statement on the back panel. \\\"Complete and balanced\\\" for your dog's specific life stage is the floor, not a feature. Then read the first three ingredients: you want a named meat (chicken, beef, lamb) leading — not \\\"meat meal,\\\" not \\\"poultry by-product,\\\" and definitely not corn, wheat, or pea protein as the anchor. Plant-first kibbles exist because plant protein is cheap, not because dogs thrive on it.\\n\\nProtein level matters more than most owners realize. Adult dogs generally do well at 22-30%, with working breeds and puppies at the higher end. The outdated \\\"low protein for seniors\\\" advice has been walked back by most veterinary nutritionists — quality matters more than quantity as dogs age, and protein restriction is only warranted with specific kidney disease diagnoses.\\n\\nA pitfall common to this category is chasing the grain-free trend. The FDA has flagged a potential DCM (heart disease) link in grain-free foods heavy in legumes and potatoes. Unless your dog has a diagnosed grain allergy — which is genuinely rare — grain-inclusive formulas from reputable brands remain the safest default. Brands like Purina Pro Plan and Hill's Science Diet fund their own veterinary nutrition research, which is part of why vets feed them to their own dogs.",
