    intro: "Treats are one of the most overlooked calorie sources in a dog's diet. The average \\\"training session\\\" delivers 30-50 rewards, and most pet-aisle treats clock in at 10-20 calories each — which means an hour of obedience work can equal a full meal's worth of junk food. Choose the wrong treat and you'll undo the exact work you're trying to reward.\\n\\nFor active training, you want pea-sized, soft, under-5-calorie treats your dog can swallow without breaking focus. Zuke's and Bocce's both nail this format; most drugstore biscuits fail on all three counts. Crunchy biscuits have their place — dental benefits, slower chewing — but they're the wrong tool for reps because the crunch time steals your timing window and the crumbs pull noses off task.\\n\\nIngredients matter, but so does matching the treat to the job. Reserve one genuinely high-value option (freeze-dried liver, real cheese, cooked chicken) as your \\\"jackpot\\\" reward for recall from distraction, vet-exam tolerance, or breakthrough moments. If your dog gets the same reward for a lazy sit and for coming off a squirrel chase, the jackpot stops working.\\n\\nA common pitfall in this category is ignoring preservatives and colors on treats that look \\\"natural.\\\" BHA, BHT, and Red 40 still appear in plenty of pet-aisle standards. The brands in our list — Zuke's, Wellness, Stewart, Bocce's, Portland Pet Food — all publish full ingredient panels without hiding behind generic terms like \\\"meat by-products\\\" or \\\"animal digest.\\\" That transparency is the signal worth paying for.",
